Conversation - Blood, which is safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated its tenth anniversary yesterday, and his president, Dr. Francine Décary, was rightfully pleased because Hema-Québec became one of the most reliable and inefficient blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he regained public confidence, which was seriously shaken by a scandal involving contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is generally known, the State reserve of blood administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Committee was contaminated by an immune deficiency virus (HIV) and a hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
As a result of this drama and the wave of public unrest, the Canadian government launched a public investigation in February 1994 by Judge Horace Krever, who was intended to explain the circumstances leading to such a tragedy and to make recommendations that such a massacre should no longer be repeated.
While Judge Krever was delaying the report, some provinces led a committee to plan a new system of blood management in Canada.
In Quebec, Géline's committee was set up.
After Gélineau and Krever's report, two suppliers were established in Canada: Hema-Québec, which was to be managed by Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society for the Conservation of All Provinces and Both Territories.
"When Hema-Québec started its activities in 1998, almost 38% of people still had confidence in the Quebec blood system," says Dr. Décary.
"The situation was overwhelming.
Through systematic efforts to increase the safety of blood products and the continued work in this area over the next few years, we have regained public confidence," he says and proudly adds that at the beginning of 2008 Hema-Québec had already trusted almost 94% of the Quebec population.
However, Dr. Décary does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is very fragile".
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the principle of discretion.
"At that time we witnessed in Europe the appearance of many cases of the human form of the disease of crazy cows, the new variants of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease," says a woman who has been leading the company since its establishment in 1998.
"And we didn't know if this disease could spread blood.
Therefore, we have relied on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau report, according to which in case we do not know, and when there is a risk of spreading a serious disease, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob’s disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, must be taken decisive measures.
So in April 1999, we refused blood from people who have stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proved that this disease was transmitted by blood.
So this episode showed us that keeping the principle of caution makes sense."
In 1999, a much more accurate HIV detection technique was found on the market: tests using nucleic acid (NAT) that enable the presence of the virus itself to be detected directly in donor blood, and not the presence of antibodies on which previously used tests were based.
NAT tests have been able to reduce the period between the patient’s infection and the moment our blood technology can be detected first, explains the specialist.
This period we have been able to reduce to less than a week.
We have significantly reduced the risk that some donors may be infected without knowing about it and not being able to find out.
This improvement has made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusions.
The risk of getting blood contaminated with HIV is that today one person out of 12 million is exposed.
"In other words, it means that before someone is infected with HIV, 12 million blood products will have to be distributed.
As a result, Hema-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products every year, it will take 24 years for the first case of HIV transmission through the blood product to appear.
I believe that we can get or prescribe the blood transfusions necessary to cure today in complete peace," says Hema-Quebek, head of management.
"The challenge for another decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what pathogen can appear in the system.
Just last year, on the island of Réunion, a chikunganya virus was discovered, which, like the West Nile virus, transmits to the blood by pumping moisture.
It is necessary to be vigilant at all times," continues Dr. Décary and stresses that, in addition to safe supplies, Hema-Québec must also be counted with sufficient supplies.
"They need to grow, because the population is getting older.
As a result of more aggressive treatment of cancer, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which is on average only 3 % of Quebecers eligible for donation."
Every healthy person is at least 18 years old, meeting the eligibility criteria, but can donate blood only once in 56 days, that means six times a year.
14% of the people offering blood are not accepted on average because they are carriers of AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they visited the country where the cold is operating, they are excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3% we can maintain a condition that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiency is very rare.
However, the members of the donor network need to be proportionately complemented by how old they are and can no longer donate blood.
However, it is difficult to convince people to give blood, especially to keep it, and to encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so unspoiled today that we will only find an hour to donate blood," Francine Décary says.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart disease, eyeballs and skin, which is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before they are stored at Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public blood bank from the dome wire in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, previously considered biomedical waste, flows rich blood to stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago we celebrated the contribution of our thousand blood sample from the dome wire to the bank, and we assume we'll take them back over a thousand years.
At the beginning of next year we should start offering them for transplants," explains Dr. Décary, who describes the blood collection program from the dome rope as very popular.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they do not have access to it," because Hema-Québec has insufficient means to offer this complex and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
