Psychology of trumpeting: Why waste more money?
In auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, to overestimate goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this well-known - and apparently irrational - behavior have been able to reveal to researchers in the field of neurology and the economy of New York University.
According to their study, published in Science magazine, people in the eBay auction competition do not want to stay, so they prefer to pay too high a price.
Research using experimental auction tried to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers sat and the other group participated in the auctions, with the method of functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) examined the active areas of the brain of subjects.
In both games, participants were able to win money, but in the event of an auction game, the key element of which is to break the other side, began to work intensively during the game, the whole of which is under the brain bark, called striatum.
This brain area plays a role other than many other functions in the "self-reparation" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, it is possible for researchers to explain how they try to avoid the rapid reaction of the striat.
In support of their theory, members of the research team from a number of economists conducted a financial cross-sectional investigation.
Under different conditions, three groups were competing against one partner.
The control group was simply informed of the real value of the product and they made the bets.
In addition, members of the other group were promised that if they left the game winning, they would receive another $15.
On the other hand, the third group received 15 dollars before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members also lost this money.
The difference between the two groups was therefore all about the fact that one was highlighted as winning and the other as losing.
However, the members of the group playing "against losing" were willing to go higher than it was in the control and "victim" group, which confirms the neurologist's hypothesis.
"These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
For so far, they have explained the phenomena that can be seen in auctions of joy from victory and avoiding risk.
When neurological imaging methods helped us to resolve the dispute between these two theories so that we have now reached the third explanation," observed Andrew Schutter, professor of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to find a doctor?
About half a billion people around the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, then in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the main causes of death.
The number of home cases of hepatitis infection is estimated to be hundreds of thousands, but only seven thousand of them are being treated. The reason is that the patient often does not know they are infected.
The name of hepatitis is the sum of the name of the infection caused by various viruses.
In their symptoms there are many similarities, which are characterized by inflammation of the liver and the jaundice, but the origins of the disease and the disease caused by them differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main ways, depending on the underlying disease: hepatitis type A and E with lawnmowers (e.g. food, water), hepatitis type B, C, D and other blood and fluids (sperm, connective tissue, saliva).
Travellers should in any case be protected by vaccination against virus A and B, and no vaccine C virus exists.
Hepatitis A symptoms occur two to three weeks after the use of an infected food, usually due to nausea, weakness, abdominal problems, vomiting.
Then on the skin and eye whites will be formed yellowish, brightish chairs and cloudy urine. Treatment may last from two to three weeks.
Each year, millions of people worldwide die of the most serious type of this disease, of liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that according to estimates, only every tenth of the infected drug is treated.
Hepatitis C may also have very serious effects: if it is not treated it may lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most people who are infected with their disease don't even know, the originator of the disease destroys the liver cells permanently, so the first symptoms are delivered in many cases up to 20-30 years.
Therefore, early prevention, regular testing is very important.
In three groups, this disease occurs much more frequently than on average: between people who underwent blood transfusions before 1991, between drug users and people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated global number of individuals infected with chronic hepatitis C 200 million is estimated.
Since the disease can already prove a routine laboratory test, a person should, in case he notices any sign of unknown origin, turn to his medical practitioner.
In early detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body, thus preventing infections and preventing cancer.
September 30th is the World Day of Hepatitis, which was organized by the organizations representing the disease for the first time worldwide in 2004.
Its aim is to highlight the chronic liver inflammation caused by these viruses, the causes of its origin and the importance of early detection of the disease.
